                </a>]]></description><media:content type="image/jpeg" url="https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5afead0c506fbe072ef6c2f7/1659475085235-W0IU4JYCQ212CB6HZIJ0/Thumb.jpg?format=1500w" medium="image" isDefault="true" width="1322" height="860"><media:title type="plain">Human Base Meshes - Gender Agnostic Topology</media:title></media:content></item><item><title>Disco Diffusion AI - Image Input</title><category>2D</category><dc:creator>Andrei Cristea</dc:creator><pubDate>Mon, 27 Jun 2022 14:51:54 +0000</pubDate><link>https://www.undoz.com/blog/2022/6/27/disco-diffusion-ai-part-2-image-input</link><guid isPermaLink="false">5afead0c506fbe072ef6c2f7:5afead6f124f1c1116b47aba:62b9c40f3137c547c5755ebb</guid><description><![CDATA[<p class="">At the moment there are few options to precisely guide the generation model. A lot of effort is being put into finding ways to make the AI more predictable, and this is probably an area where considerable portion of research is going to be focused on in the future. I can see more advanced models being guided by features in the style of <a href="https://www.nvidia.com/en-us/studio/canvas/">NVIDIA Canvas.</a> <br><br>I am mostly here for the abstract and unexpected factors, so I don’t mind it too much. <br>I wish interdepended parameters would be linked together by a factor. Changing things like steps and resolution should try and keep the result relatively consistent and scale other parameters that depend on screen space or sampling areas.<br></p><p class="">The image input option in Disco Diffusion allows you to seed the initial steps of the model with your own input, and be able to suggest the overall composition or to “remix” our input with different prompts. <br>The symmetry model is very valuable for generating designs, especially when it comes to character art. <br></p><p class="">Here’s a series of experiments using the same image source:</p>



































  

    
  
    

      

      
